# -*- mode:org;coding:utf-8 -*-
#+TITLE: a lisp-interactor configuration (lisp.conf), stacked under aldo.conf
#+AUTHOR: Pascal J. Bourguignon
#+DATE: 2026-07-22

From pjb's point-6 answer in =interactor-design-revision.issue=: the
LISP (REPL) interactor needs its own persistent configuration, and
configurations STACK like the interactors do.

* Design (pjb)

- A lisp configuration file (lisp.conf), like aldo.conf; its first
  setting is the same =sedit-on-quit auto-save|do-not-save|ask= —
  governing =(clal-sedit …)= invocations from the REPL, while the aldo
  setting of the same name governs debugger-side invocations.
- Stacking: at the LISP interactor only lisp.conf is active; in the
  debugger both aldo.conf AND lisp.conf are active, aldo over lisp — a
  setting absent from aldo.conf but present in lisp.conf is taken from
  lisp.conf (for common settings).
- Writes go to the ACTIVE interactor's own configuration: =set
  sedit-on-quit …= at the debugger modifies only the aldo
  configuration (shadowing lisp's even when the key was not previously
  present in aldo.conf); at the REPL it modifies lisp.conf.

* Current state (1.4.48)

- =sedit-on-quit= exists as an ALDO setting (default =ask=) and is
  consulted by the NAV->SEDIT bridge; the REPL-side =(clal-sedit …)=
  uses the built-in default (=ask=) — no lisp.conf yet, no REPL =,set=
  command, no stacked lookup.

* To do

- A settings table + conf file for the LISP interactor (XDG path like
  aldo's), with =sedit-on-quit= as its first key.
- A REPL =,set NAME VALUE= / =,settings= command pair over it.
- The stacked lookup (aldo over lisp) for common settings, and
  write-to-the-active-layer semantics.
- Route the CLAL-SEDIT builtin's :on-quit thunk through the stacked
  lookup instead of the built-in default.
